n through email delivery — reaches the configured recipient's inbox correctly","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This end-to-end test involves multiple sequential steps: (1) data collection from three sources (System/Integration), (2) LLM-based narrative generation (Agentic), (3) email delivery to SMTP (System). Since at least one step (narrative generation) is Agentic, and the failure can only be caught by running the full pipeline with real LLM calls and real or realistic email delivery infrastructure, the minimum is Workflow. A unit test of any single step would miss failures in the orchestration, LLM output quality, or email delivery logic.","test_description":"Set up a complete test harness: mock or stage the three data sources (HTTP mock servers or fixtures), use a real LLM API call (or high-fidelity proxy) for narrative generation, and use a local SMTP mock server or test email service (e.g., MailHog, SendGrid sandbox). Execute the full scheduled report pipeline. Verify: (1) all three sources are called and contribute to data, (2) narrative is generated without errors, (3) email is composed with correct To/From/Subject, (4) email body includes the narrative summary, (5) SMTP delivery succeeds and message appears in the mock inbox.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.7}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When email delivery service is unreachable, generated report is saved to local file and delivery is retried on next scheduled run","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This test requires real filesystem I/O and a realistic email service failure condition. The failures to catch are: (1) report is discarded instead of saved, (2) saved to wrong path or wrong format, (3) retry logic doesn't actually retry the saved report, (4) concurrent runs cause file conflicts. Unit tests with mocked filesystem would always pass. System-level testing with real local filesystem operations and a simulatable email failure (mock SMTP that rejects connection, or timeout) is necessary to verify the fallback and retry behavior works in practice.","test_description":"Configure the report generator with a temporary local directory for fallback saves. Use a mock SMTP server that simulates unreachability (connection refused or timeout). Execute the report pipeline. Verify: (1) the SMTP error is caught, (2) the generated report is written to the configured fallback directory with correct filename and format (JSON, markdown, etc.), (3) file contents are valid and complete. Run the pipeline again and verify: (4) the retry logic identifies the pending report from the previous run, (5) re-attempts email delivery, (6) cleans up the file on successful delivery (or marks it as delivered).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13289,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13289},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5b8f7f63-2adb-40ee-94e7-cb6609933c33","uuid":"a5248e85-ae29-4f90-804f-134358ea1201"}
